A group of masked pro-separatists kept away from the gendarmes bombarded them with eggs and powder paint, creating dark clouds of dust on the streets that were usually flooded by tourists.
The stabbing later intensified, with the police using their batons to control the situation.
For several hours, pro-independence groups chanted “We don’t forget, we don’t forgive,” while union protesters shouted “Long live Spain!”
14 people have received medical care for minor injuries caused during the protests, according to local media.
Tensions remain high in the region that wants to become independent a year after the October 1 referendum was deemed illegal by Madrid but celebrated by Catalan separatists.
Voters voted, overwhelmingly, to become independent, although turnout was low, and those against secession largely boycotted the vote.
According to Catalan authorities, nearly 100 people were injured last year after police tried to stop voting at polling stations in the region, with violent clashes taking place.
Pro-independence groups camped overnight on Friday night to prevent a demonstration in support of the national police.
The demonstration continued, but the protesters were forced to choose a new path.
Narcissus Termes, 68, an electrician who took part in the separatist protest with his wife, said he no longer had any hope of gaining independence from Catalonia.
“Last year I had some of the best moments of my life.
I looked at my parents crying with joy that I can vote, but now we have nothing to do,” he said.
Despite achieving a vital but narrow victory in the regional elections in December last year, Catalan pro-independent parties have tried to maintain momentum this year, with many of the most well-known leaders either in exile or in detention, awaiting trial for their role in organising the referendum.
Joan Puig, a 42-year-old mechanic who recorded the police protest on his phone, said politicians on both sides fueled the conflict.
“The situation is becoming increasingly tense,” he said.
On Saturday, Oriol Junqueras, one of the nine Catalan leaders in prison since the end of last year, announced that he would run for election to the European Parliament next year.
“As a candidate for the European elections, it is the best way to denounce the regression in democratic values and the repression we have seen from the Spanish government,” he said.
