Macedonians will vote in a referendum if they want to change the name of the country
On Sunday, Macedonian citizens voted in a referendum if they want the country’s name changed to “Republic of North Macedonia,” a change that would resolve a decade-old dispute with Greece that opposed its accession to the European Union and NATO.
Greece, which includes a province called Macedonia, claims that the name of the neighbouring country represents a claim on its territory and has opposed its accession to the EU and NATO.
The two governments agreed in June on the proposed new name, but opposition nationalists argue that this change would undermine the ethnic identity of the majority Slavic population of Macedonia.
President Gjorge Ivanov said he would not vote in the referendum and that a boycott campaign had cast doubt on the presence of the vote, and it was possible that the minimum threshold of 50% needed to validate the referendum could not be reached.
The question on the ballot in the referendum will be: “Do you agree to join the EU and NATO, accepting the agreement with Greece?”.
Proponents of the name change, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, say it is a price that must be paid by Macedonia, one of the countries that resulted from the break-up of Yugoslavia, in order to be accepted into entities such as the EU and NATO.
“I am here today to vote for the future of the country, for young people in Macedonia to live freely under the umbrella of the European Union, because it means safer lives for all of us,” said 79-year-old Olivera Georgijevska in Skopje.
Although it is not legally binding, quite a few members of parliament have said they will respect the outcome of the vote to make it decisive.
For the name to be changed, a two-thirds quorum is required in parliament.
The state election commission said no irregularities had been reported by 1 p.m.
However, turnout was only 16%, compared to 34% in the last parliamentary elections in 2016 when 66% of eligible voters cast their ballots.
“I came to vote for my children and for our place in Europe,” said Gjose Tanevski, 62, a voter from Skopje, the country’s capital.
On September 30, 2018, Macedonia’s Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, his wife, Zorica, and their son, Dushko, voted for a referendum on changing Macedonia’s name, which will allow them to join NATO and enter the European Union.
In front of the parliament in Skopje, 54-year-old Vladimir Kavardarkov prepared a small-sized scene and threw chairs in front of tents raised by those who would boycott the referendum.
“We support NATO and the EU, but we want to join them at the top, not the back door,” Kavadarkov said.
“We are a poor country, but we have dignity.
If we are not wanted by the name of Macedonia, we can go to other countries, such as China and Russia, and we can become part of the Eurasian Union."
Prime Minister Zaev said NATO membership would bring much-needed investment to Macedonia, which has an unemployment rate of more than 20 percent.
"I think the majority will be in favor of changing the name, because more than 80% of our citizens are in favor of joining NATO and the EU," Zaev said after casting his vote.
He said a result in favor of changing the name would be "confirmation of our future".
According to a poll published last month by the Institute for Policy Research, between 30% and 43% of citizens with the right to vote will participate in the referendum, under the necessary number of participants.
According to another poll conducted by Telma TV in Macedonia, 57% of respondents plan to vote on Sunday.
Of these, 70% said they would vote in favour of the change.
In order for the referendum to be valid, the voter turnout must be 50% plus one vote.
The failure of the referendum would represent the first serious blow to pro-Western government policy since the takeover of the government in May last year.
