Independent schools in Scotland maintain a record of academic excellence, and this continued in 2018 with another set of exceptional exam results, which is underpinned by individual and collective successes in sport, art, music and other community efforts.
With over 30,000 students in Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide services at the highest level to their students and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for high school and higher education, their chosen career and their place as global citizens.
As an educational sector that can conceive and implement a special school curriculum, we note that modern languages continue to be a popular and desirable topic of choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, your words will come to his mind.
If you speak to him in his own language, the words reach his heart.”
This is a strong reminder that we can’t just rely on English when we want to build relationships and trust people from other countries.
Based on the recent results of this year’s competition, we note that foreign languages are at the top of the rankings, with the highest promotion rates in independent schools.
A total of 68% of students who studied foreign languages obtained a Higher Grade A certificate.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72% of students obtained a Higher Grade A certificate in Mandarin; also, 72% of those who study German, 69% of those who study French, and 63% of those who study Spanish obtained such a certificate.
This demonstrates that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as vital skills that children and young people will certainly need in the future.
Now, foreign languages, as a matter, hold the same as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in independent school curricula and in other fields.
A 2014 survey by the UK’s Employment and Skills Commission found that, for reasons employers gave for the fight to fill vacancies, 17% were attributed to a language skills shortage.
Therefore, more and more, language skills become imperative for preparing young people for their future careers.
With more job opportunities that require foreign languages, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career one chooses, if they have learned a second language, they will have a real advantage in the future, having such a skill throughout life.
The ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will automatically put a multilingual person before the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of over 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75% were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to carry on a conversation, and French was the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage, 15%.
Therefore, investing in foreign language learning is important for today’s children.
Having more languages, especially in countries with a developing economy, children will be more likely to find meaningful jobs.
In Scotland, each school will teach other foreign languages.
A number of schools will focus on more modern classical languages, while others will learn languages that are considered to be most important to the UK when looking ahead to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child’s interest, there will always be more languages of choice within independent schools, with teaching staff who are specialized in this field.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that will prepare children and encourage them with the skills they need to succeed, no matter what the future holds.
It cannot be denied at this time, in a global business environment, that languages continue to be vital to the future of the country, so it must be reflected in education.
Indeed, modern languages should indeed be considered "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
It has to be done (it has to be done).
