Harvard students take courses on how to get enough rest
A new Harvard University course this year encourages students to sleep longer, in an attempt to combat the growing “macho” culture that makes them subject themselves to “all-night” learning sessions energized with lots of caffeine.
A scientist has discovered that students at the world’s most prestigious university often don’t even master the basic concepts of how they should take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, is the one who created the course, which is believed to be the first of its kind in the US.
He was inspired to create the course after giving a lecture on the impact of sleep deprivation on the ability to learn.
“In the end, a girl came to me and said, ‘Why am I being told this just now, in the last year?’
She told me that she had never been told about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, introduced for the first time this year, explains to students the essential concepts of how good sleep habits help improve academic and athletic performance, as well as overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students were seriously sleep deprived during the week.
An hour-long course can involve a number of interactive tasks.
Within one section is presented the image of a bedroom, and students can click on coffee mugs, curtains, sports pants and books to tell them what are the effects of caffeine and light and how athletic performance is affected by sleep deficiency, but also about the importance of a sleep program.
In another section, participants were told how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression, and cancer.
A campus map, with interactive icons, encourages participants to think about their daily schedule.
“We know we can’t change students’ behavior instantly.
But we believe that they have a right to know, just as anyone has a right to know what the health effects of smoking are," Professor Czeisler added.
The culture that makes students proud to have learned all night still exists, he says, adding that modern technology and the increasing pressure on students have turned sleep deprivation into a growing problem.
Enough sleep, of good quality, should be a student’s “secret weapon” for combating stress, exhaustion, and anxiety, he said, and even to avoid weight gain because sleep deprivation makes the brain think that the body is hungry, which makes students feel that they are hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California student studying chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler create the course after attending one of his first year courses at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to promote a course for all students.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all post-graduate students to complete a similar degree program before enrolling in this institution where competition is fierce.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students program an alarm to know when it is time to go to bed, as well as for the waking hour, and to know what are the harmful effects of the "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LEDs, which can disturb the circadian rhythm and cause difficulty in waking up.
