Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity, an invention that eventually led to the creation of the device known as the Geiger counter.
An essential device for science ever since, the Geiger counter has also become essential for pop culture, as happened in the film The Bells of San Coronado (1950), in which they played Roy Rogers and Dale Evans in the role of cowboys with unlikely proclivities to science:
Man: “What’s that?”
Rogers: “It’s a Geiger counter, used to locate radioactive minerals, like uranium.
