National Trust Spying on the Secret Life of Bats
New research that is being conducted on a property in the Scottish Highlands wants to reveal how bats use their environment to hunt their prey.
It is hoped that the findings will reveal new things about the behavior of these unique flying mammals and help future conservation activities.
The study by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland will look at common dwarf bats and pygmy bats, as well as eared bats and water bats from the Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording devices will be placed in key locations around the property to track the activity of bats throughout the season.
The NHS team and volunteers will also conduct mobile studies using manual detectors.
Specialized audio analysis of all recordings will estimate the frequency of sounds made by bats and what species emit certain sounds.
There will also be a habitat map and a report, to create a detailed picture, on a scale, of their behavior in the environment.
Rob Dewar, a conservation consultant for NTS, hopes the results will reveal which areas in the habitat are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as lawn creation, and which is the best way to maintain forest meadows for bats and other associated species.
Populations of bats in Scotland and across the UK have declined considerably in the last century.
They are endangered by the construction and development work that affects their nests, but also by habitat loss.
And wind turbines and public lighting are risks, as are fly traps and some chemical treatments for building materials, but also domestic cat attacks.
Actually, bats are not blind.
However, due to the fact that they hunt at night, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echolocation technique to accurately identify the insects and obstacles on their flight path.
NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important parks and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, is thinking very seriously about bats.
They have ten trained experts, who conduct periodic studies, control nests, and sometimes perform rescue missions.
The organization created the very first and only bat reserve in Scotland, on the Threeve estate in Dumfries and Galloway, where eight out of ten species of bats are found in Scotland.
The estate’s manager, David Thompson, says this is the ideal territory for bats.
“Here at Threeve, the area is great for bats,” he says.
“We have old buildings, lots of old trees and a perfect habitat.
But there are many things we don’t know about bats, so the work we do here and elsewhere will help us understand why they need to multiply.”
It stresses the importance of looking for bats before carrying out maintenance work at properties, because the simple unintentional destruction of a maternal nest could kill up to 400 females and chicks, which can destroy the entire local population.
Bats are protected, and killing, harassing or disturbing them, as well as destroying their nests, are prohibited actions.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish official at the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to help.
She said: “We still have a lot to learn about bats and we don’t know how populations evolve for many of our species.”
