Foreign buyers will be charged a higher court fee for buying a property in the UK, and the extra money will be used to help homeless people, as Theresa May is due to announce today.
The change will be seen as an attempt to neutralize Jeremy Corbyn’s efforts to attract young people with the right to vote, promising more affordable homes and targeting high-income people.
The higher stamp duty will be applied to natural and legal persons who are not taxpayers in the United Kingdom, and the additional money thus obtained will be used to support the Government’s efforts to help the homeless.
The surcharge, which adds to the current stamp legal fee, including the high levels last two years for the second property and properties purchased for rental purposes, could reach a value of 3%.
