How can the trade war between the United States and China be beneficial for Beijing?
The salvos that heralded the start of the trade war between the United States and China have been heartbreaking, and while there seems to be a long way to go, the fighting between the two countries could be beneficial for Beijing in the long run, experts say.
Donald Trump, the president of the United States, issued the first warning earlier this year by imposing taxes on key imports from China, including solar panels, steel and aluminum.
The biggest escalation this week came with new taxes affecting $200 billion worth of goods (<0xC2><0xA3>150 billion), effectively imposing taxes on half of all goods in China that reach the United States.
Beijing has retaliated each time, most recently imposing a tax of between 5 and 10% on US products worth $60 billion.
China has warned it will respond to every blow from the United States and it is unlikely that the world’s second-largest economy will take a step back in the near future.
For Washington to withdraw, China must agree to its demands, but publicly giving in to the United States would be far too humiliating for Xi Jinping, the president of China.
However, experts say that if Beijing plays its cards well, U.S. trade war pressures could positively support China in the long run, reducing the interdependence of the two economies.
