Red tide news: concentrations have dropped in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report by the Florida Wildlife Protection Commission shows a general decline in red tide concentrations for certain areas of the Gulf of Tampa.
According to the Commission, non-uniform inflorescence conditions are reported in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties – suggesting a decrease in concentrations.
This inflorescence of the red tide extends over an area of the coast of about 210 km, from northern Pinellas County to southern Lee County.
The spots can be found about 10 miles (16 km) offshore of Hillsborough County, but in fewer places than last week.
The red sea was also observed in Pasco County.
The average concentrations found in Pinellas County or off it were reported last week to be low to high concentrations in Hillsborough County, high to high concentrations in Manatee County, high to high concentrations in Sarasota County or off it, high to low concentrations in Charlotte County, and low to high concentrations in Hillsborough County.
Respiratory irritations continue to be reported in the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
No cases of respiratory irritation have been reported in the northwestern U.S. state of Florida in the past week.
